REvenge Installer - Auto-Delete Mechanism

HOW IT WORKS

Overview
The installer automatically deletes the downloaded setup file (REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe) after the installation process completes and the setup window closes.

Step-by-Step Process

1. Download & Launch Phase

User clicks "Download & Install" button
   |
   V
Multi-threaded download starts (4 concurrent threads)
   |
   V
File saved to: C:\Users\[Username]\Downloads\REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe
   |
   V
When download completes -> ShellExecute opens the setup file


2. Monitoring Thread Creation

When the setup file is successfully downloaded and launched, a separate detached thread is spawned that:

std::thread([hw,filePath=g_savePath](){
    WatchAndDeleteFile(filePath);
    PostMessage(hw, WM_CLOSE, 0, 0);
}).detach();

This thread:
- Captures the file path (g_savePath)
- Captures the main window handle (hw)
- Runs independently of the main application
- Will close the installer after the deletion is complete


3. Process Monitoring

The WatchAndDeleteFile() function performs the following steps:

Step 1: Wait for setup process to start
   Sleep(2000);
   This gives the operating system time to launch the REvenge_Setup.exe process

Step 2: Find REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe by name
   HANDLE snap = CreateToolhelp32Snapshot(TH32CS_SNAPPROCESS, 0);
   Iterate through all running processes
   Search for process named "REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe"
   Get its Process ID (PID)
   Close snapshot handle

Step 3: Wait for process to close
   HANDLE hProc = OpenProcess(SYNCHRONIZE, FALSE, targetPid);
   WaitForSingleObject(hProc, INFINITE);
   This blocks execution until the user closes the setup window
   Once the process exits, execution continues
   CloseHandle(hProc);

Step 4: Delete the file
   Sleep(2000);
   This waits 2 seconds to let the operating system release file locks
   DeleteFileW(filePath.c_str());
   Permanently deletes the file from disk


4. Timeline Visualization

T=0s     User clicks Download button

T=0-30s  4 threads download file in parallel
         Thread 1: downloads bytes 0-25MB
         Thread 2: downloads bytes 25-50MB
         Thread 3: downloads bytes 50-75MB
         Thread 4: downloads bytes 75-100MB

T=30s    Download complete
         ShellExecute -> REvenge_Setup.exe launches
         Monitoring thread STARTS (independent)

T=32s    Setup window opens (user sees installer)
         
         User performs installation...

T=120s   User closes setup window
         REvenge_Setup.exe process terminates

T=122s   Monitoring thread detects process exit
         Waits 2 seconds for file locks to release
         Deletes REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe

T=123s   File is gone from Downloads folder
         Main installer also closes


KEY FEATURES

No Console Window
Uses native Win32 API directly, not cmd.exe

No User Interaction
Completely automatic and silent, zero user action required

Reliable Timing
Uses WaitForSingleObject() which waits until the actual process exits, not a timer

Unicode Support
Handles file paths with Cyrillic characters, spaces, and special characters

Independent Execution
Detached thread survives application closure

Process Detection
Searches by exact executable name using CreateToolhelp32Snapshot


FILE PATH HANDLING

Input:  C:\Users\Пользователь\Downloads\REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe

Features:
- Supports Cyrillic characters
- Supports spaces in path
- Supports UNC network paths
- Supports very long paths

Deletion: Guaranteed at exact same path where file was downloaded


ERROR HANDLING

Scenario 1: Process not found in 60 seconds
Default behavior: Wait 60 seconds, then delete anyway
This prevents orphaned files if setup fails to launch

Scenario 2: File locked by antivirus
Waits 2 additional seconds after process exit
This gives the operating system time to release file handles

Scenario 3: Path invalid or corrupted
DeleteFileW() silently fails without showing error to user
In this case, the setup file wasn't downloaded anyway


TECHNICAL STACK

Language: C++17
API: Windows Win32 API (no external dependencies)
Threading: std::thread with lambda capture
Process Management: CreateToolhelp32Snapshot, OpenProcess, WaitForSingleObject
File Operations: Native DeleteFileW() function
Compatibility: Windows 10, Windows 11


WHY THIS APPROACH

Advantages:
- Runs in background without showing any UI
- No cmd.exe window spawned
- Truly waits for process exit (not time-based guessing)
- Works with any file path encoding
- No external tools required
- Simple, reliable, foolproof

Alternatives that were rejected:
- cmd.exe /c timeout && del
  Problem: Shows console window, time-based deletion
  
- Registry cleanup
  Problem: Overkill, requires admin permissions
  
- Batch file
  Problem: Requires creating temporary file, less reliable
  
- Scheduled task
  Problem: Requires elevated privileges, too complex


SUMMARY

The auto-delete mechanism works by:

1. Starting a separate thread when download completes
2. Thread finds the REvenge_Setup_1.5.0.exe process by name
3. Thread waits until user closes the setup window
4. Process detection works even if main installer window closes
5. Once setup process exits, waits 2 seconds for file locks
6. Permanently deletes the downloaded file
7. Returns control to close the main installer window

This ensures that the temporary setup file never remains on the user's computer, saving disk space and keeping the system clean.

